WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.444
Let's break down interstitial lung
disease, or ILD.

2
00:00:03.984 --> 00:00:07.505
This is a group of disorders that cause
progressive scarring of lung tissue,

3
00:00:07.885 --> 00:00:10.185
leading to stiff, noncompliant lungs.

4
00:00:10.824 --> 00:00:12.145
The key idea is this.

5
00:00:12.704 --> 00:00:14.625
ILD is a restrictive disease.

6
00:00:15.444 --> 00:00:18.565
Unlike asthma or COPD, this is not an
airflow problem.

7
00:00:18.825 --> 00:00:19.965
It's a volume problem.

8
00:00:20.524 --> 00:00:24.405
The lungs cannot expand normally because
fibrosis makes them stiff.

9
00:00:25.145 --> 00:00:26.424
Here's the cause to effect flow.

10
00:00:27.184 --> 00:00:30.704
Something triggers inflammation in the
interstitium, which is the space

11
00:00:30.704 --> 00:00:32.485
between the alveoli and capillaries.

12
00:00:33.244 --> 00:00:35.625
Over time, that inflammation turns into
fibrosis.

13
00:00:36.305 --> 00:00:39.444
That scarring thickens the alveolar
membrane, slows diffusion,

14
00:00:39.825 --> 00:00:40.965
and leads to hypoxemia.

15
00:00:42.025 --> 00:00:45.084
Clinically, patients usually present with
progressive shortness of breath,

16
00:00:45.665 --> 00:00:47.884
a dry, nonproductive cough, and reduced

17
00:00:47.884 --> 00:00:48.865
exercise tolerance.

18
00:00:49.025 --> 00:00:51.845
On auscultation, you'll often hear fine
crackles,

19
00:00:52.244 --> 00:00:53.865
sometimes described as Velcro-like.

20
00:00:54.505 --> 00:00:59.284
One key respiratory therapy clue is that
oxygen levels drop with activity before they

21
00:00:59.284 --> 00:00:59.985
drop at rest.

22
00:01:00.924 --> 00:01:02.465
Diagnostics follow a classic pattern.

23
00:01:03.384 --> 00:01:08.345
Pulmonary function tests show a
restrictive pattern with decreased FVC and a normal or

24
00:01:08.345 --> 00:01:10.665
increased FEV1 to FVC ratio.

25
00:01:11.565 --> 00:01:15.404
ABGs may show early respiratory alkalosis,
but as the disease

26
00:01:15.404 --> 00:01:18.125
progresses, hypoxemia becomes more
prominent.

27
00:01:19.385 --> 00:01:21.764
Imaging, especially CT, may show ground

28
00:01:21.764 --> 00:01:24.724
glass opacities, reticular patterns, or
honeycombing.

29
00:01:25.345 --> 00:01:26.224
Watch for red flags.

30
00:01:26.745 --> 00:01:30.184
Increasing oxygen requirements, worsening
dyspnea, and

31
00:01:30.184 --> 00:01:32.605
signs of pulmonary hypertension all
suggest progression.

32
00:01:33.504 --> 00:01:36.025
These patients can decline gradually or
sometimes rapidly.

33
00:01:37.184 --> 00:01:40.224
Management focuses on slowing progression
and supporting oxygenation.

34
00:01:41.004 --> 00:01:44.404
Many patients require supplemental oxygen,
especially during activity.

35
00:01:45.165 --> 00:01:48.184
Antifibrotic medications may be used
depending on the type of ILD.

36
00:01:49.125 --> 00:01:52.684
Pulmonary rehab can improve function, and
in advanced cases,

37
00:01:52.944 --> 00:01:54.144
lung transplant may be considered.

38
00:01:54.144 --> 00:01:57.324
As a respiratory therapist, your role is
critical.

39
00:01:57.985 --> 00:02:01.264
You are monitoring oxygenation trends,
assessing work of breathing,

40
00:02:01.544 --> 00:02:03.504
and identifying early signs of decline.

41
00:02:04.165 --> 00:02:08.445
You also help titrate oxygen and educate
patients on proper use and expectations.

42
00:02:08.725 --> 00:02:10.925
For board prep, remember this pattern.

43
00:02:11.664 --> 00:02:14.925
Progressive dyspnea, dry cough,
restrictive PFTs,

44
00:02:15.024 --> 00:02:17.505
and fibrotic changes on imaging point
toward ILD.

45
00:02:17.964 --> 00:02:22.485
The main takeaway is that ILD is about
stiff lungs that cannot oxygenate effectively.

46
00:02:23.074 --> 00:02:25.464
Your job is to recognize it, support the
patient,

47
00:02:25.785 --> 00:02:26.925
and know when things are getting worse.

